## Analysis

Throughout the analysis, we leverage a causal inference framework to estimate the effect of being in the pre-election or post-election period. In the *2020 Western States* data, assignment to the pre- or post- election period is not randomized. Instead, we were fortuitously collecting data over an extended period during the 2020 presidential election, an election in which the results were unknown on election day. In the *2024 Western States* data, assignment to the pre- or post- election period is randomized; respondents were randomly assigned to be interviewed before or after the election results were known. In both datasets, we aim to estimate the treatment effect of being in the pre-election versus post-election period on support for electoral contestation behaviors. According to the *winner-loser* hypothesis, the treatment effect should vary depending on whether the respondent voted for a winning or losing candidate. 

We use *g-computation* to estimate the conditional marginal effects of being in the pre-election versus post-election period, where the marginal effect should vary by vote choice (Trump versus Biden in 2020; Trump versus Harris in 2024). First, we fit an *outcome* regression model, an electoral contestation item (e.g., support for attending a march) as a function of *pre* versus *post* election, *vote choice*, the *interaction between vote choice and pre/post election*, *age*, *Latino*, whether the respondent has a four-year *college degree*, and *gender*.  Following estimation, we then simulate (using the posterior distribution) support for electoral contestation behaviors under both treatment conditions (pre-election and post-election), which allows us to estimate individual level treatment effects. From here, we just summarize these individual level treatment effects among Trump versus Biden/Harris voters, a *conditional marginal effect*.

Here, we focus on *five* contestation items in both datasets, (1) support for attending a march, (2) support for criticizing the election results, (3) support for burning the American flag, (4) support for taking the matter to court, and (5) support for requesting a recount. Each item is measured on a 5-point scale: (1) Strongly Oppose, (2) Oppose, (3) Neutral, (4) Support, and (5) Strongly Support. 

Three parameterizations for the outcome equations are used.

(1) An *ordered logit* model is estimated for each item, recoding the 5-point scale into three categories: (1) Support (4 and 5), (2) Neutral (3), and (3) Oppose (1 and 2). For this plot, we only present the *Support* category, and the corresponding probability and marginal effects estimates.

(2) A *multinomial logit* model is estimated for each item, again using the recoded data (1) Support (4 and 5), (2) Neutral (3), and (3) Oppose (1 and 2). For this plot, we only present the *Support* category, and the corresponding probability and marginal effects estimates. This relaxes the *parallel lines* assumption in the *ordinal model*, that covariates have the same effect across all categories.

(3) A *linear regression* model is estimated for each item, retaining the 5-point scale. For this plot, we use the `vayr` package to show mean estimates alongisde observed distributions.




